Mitral valve prolapse has been largely underestimated as a cardiac pathology responsible of SCD in the athlete by general and forensic pathologists. This may be explained by the traditional perspective that MVP is a common valve variant with an estimated prevalence in the general population of 2–3%. Hence, it is deemed to be an uncertain or unlikely cause of SCD at postmortem investigation. Although it is generally regarded as a benign condition, malignant ventricular arrhythmias and SCD have been reported; the incidence of SCD in MVP has been estimated to range from 0.2%/year to 0.4%/year in prospective follow-up studies [16]. Using rigorous criteria for morphologic diagnosis (i.e., myxomatous mitral valve) at postmortem, MVP has been implicated in 7% of all cases of juvenile SCD in the Registry of the Veneto region of Italy. Recent clinico-pathologic studies on MVP patients with arrhythmias or SCD victims provided new insights into our understanding of the underlying myocardial substrate [17], [18]. Revision of the histologic features in SCD victims demonstrated the presence of myocardial fibrosis affecting both the infero-basal LV free wall (under the posterior leaflet) and the papillary muscle [17]. The scarring process may be caused by the mechanical stretch of the inferobasal wall and papillary muscles secondary to the excessive mobility of the valve leaflets due to by posterior systolic curling, eventually leading to myocardial hypertrophy and fibrosis [18]. Most important, the presence and location of myocardial fibrosis observed at histology in SCD victims were confirmed in living patients with MVP and ventricular arrhythmias by demonstration of LGE at CE-CMR. This suggests a promising role of CE-CMR for arrhythmic risk stratification beyond traditional electrophysiological markers. The athlete with at-risk arrhythmic MVP can be identified at pre-participation screening based on the following characteristics: a young adult (most often woman) with a mid-systolic click at auscultation, T-wave abnormalities on inferior leads and complex ventricular arrhythmias with a right bundle branch block morphology on ECG, and bi-leaflet involvement of the mitral valve on echocardiography [17]. These clinical features may help to select a high-risk subgroup of patients which are candidates for further evaluation by CE-CMR.
5. SCD in older athletes
The risk of sports-related acute cardiovascular events, including SCD, increases exponentially among individuals aged >35 years and is almost exclusively related to the development and progression of atherosclerotic coronary artery disease [3]. Whereas ECG screening has been proven to be lifesaving in young competitive athletes in whom SCD is mostly caused by ECG-detectable genetic cardiomyopathies, it appears to be non accurate for identification of coronary artery disease in asymptomatic middle aged/senior athletes [1]. Because of its established prognostic value, widespread availability and low cost, exercise testing is widely deemed the best available test for screening asymptomatic adults prior to an exercise programme [19]. However, the test accuracy for detection of coronary artery disease is limited among the general population because of the relatively low disease's prevalence. The test performance increases with a greater pre-test probability of coronary atherosclerosis, i.e. in subjects with multiple risk factors for coronary artery disease. According to current recommendations for preparticipation cardiovascular evaluation in adults, the assessment of risk is based on age, sex, blood pressure, blood cholesterol, and smoking history, using available scoring systems such as the ESC Systematic Coronary Risk Evaluation (SCORE) [19]. Maximal exercise testing (and possibly further cardiologic evaluations) is reserved to those individuals embarking in moderate/intense physical activity who show an increased risk for coronary events.
6. Conclusions
The available evidence indicates that ECG screening has to be considered an efficient health strategy for prevention of SCD of young competitive athletes. The development of modern criteria for interpretation of athlete's ECG is expected to improve the accuracy of screening athletes for cardiovascular disease, with a lower proportion of false-positive results, and lead to a considerable cost savings in the context of a preparticipation screening process. On the other hand, no screening strategy will identify all athletes at risk of SCD, particularly those affected by cardiac conditions such as congenital anomalies of coronary arteries or atherosclerotic coronary artery disease, who usually have no abnormalities on 12-lead ECG. Moreover, cardiac arrest due to blunt chest trauma (commotio cordis) cannot be prevented by screening. Such screening limitations justify the increasing efforts for implementing cardiopulmonary resuscitation intervention programmes including early external defibrillation by automated external defibrillator for treating unpredictable arrhythmic cardiac arrest events in the athletic field [20].
